<h1>To Captain John Manley</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge 28th Jany 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I received your agreeable Letter of the 26th instant giveing an account of your haveing taken &amp; Carried into Plymouth two of the Enemys transports. Your Conduct in engageing the eight Gun Schooner, with So few hands as you went out with, your attention in Secureing Your prizes, &amp; your general good behavior since you first engaged in the Service, merits mine &amp; your Countrys thanks.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>You may be assured that every attention will be paid to any reasonable request of yours, &amp; that you shall have the Comand of a Stronger vessell of War, but as it will take up Some time before Such a one Can be fitted out, my desire is, that You Continue in the Hancock, until the end [of the]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> CruizeWhen that is out you will Come to Head qrs &amp; we will Confer together on the subject of the other ship[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> I wish you Coud engage men at Plymouth to make your Complement at least 40 Strong it woud enable you to encounter the small tenders that may fall in your waytho I woud rather have you avoid an engagement untill you have a ship that will place you upon a more equall footing with your enemyI need not reccommend to you to proceed again &amp; pursue your good fortune, I wish you Coud inspire the Captains of the other Armed schooners under your
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0207">[207]</span>
Command with Some of your activity &amp; IndustryCannot You appoint Such Stations for themwhere they may have the best Chance of intercepting Supplies Going to the enemy[.] they dare not disobey your orders, as it is mentioned in the instructions I have given to each of them, that they are to be under your Comand, as Comodore<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> &amp; as Such I desire that you will give them Such Instructions in writeing as to you will appear proper for the good of the Service[.] I am Sir wishing You a Continuance of Success.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, in Stephen Moylans writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Manleys letter to GW of 26 Jan. has not been found. For his capture of the ships <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Happy Return</span> and <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Norfolk</span> on 25 Jan. and his engagement with the British tender <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">General Gage</span> that day, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0138" class="document">William Watson to GW, 26</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0155" class="document">2930 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The words within square brackets are taken from the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Manley continued to command the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Hancock</span> until April when he became a captain in the Continental navy. See <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:290, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0161" class="document">Artemas Ward to GW, 3 May 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0149-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0103" class="document">GWs instructions to Charles Dyar, 20 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
